The '''Michigan State Spartans men's basketball''' team represents [[Michigan State University]] (MSU) and competes in the [[Big Ten Conference]] of [[NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]]. The team currently plays at the [[Breslin Student Events Center]]. The men's basketball program is considered one of college basketball's elite, an annual NCAA Tournament contender <ref>{{cite web|title=Blue bloods reign in Friday's |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/9151/bluebloods-reign-in-fridays-late-action|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=March 27, 2010}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Tennessee hopes to get where Mich. St. has been|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/36068315/ns/sports-college_basketball/|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=March 27, 2010}}</ref>.
Michigan State men's basketball team has a long history that is rich in tradition. The team has won two NCAA championships and 12 [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] championships in men's basketball. The Spartans won the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|National Championship]] in both the [[1979 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1979 NCAA Tournament]] and [[2000 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2000 NCAA Tournament]]. The 1979 National Championship story line was [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rNkyv4S67EU highly touted as Magic vs. Bird]. It was achieved by a team under the coaching of [[Jud Heathcote]] that included MVP [[Magic Johnson]], [[Greg Kelser]] and [[Jay Vincent]]. MSU beat the then undefeated [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State Sycamores]], led by future NBA hall of famer [[Larry Bird]]. The [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rvo44lkyLCo 2000 National Championship] was achieved by [[Morris Peterson]], A.J. Granger, [[Charlie Bell (basketball)|Charlie Bell]], [[Jason Richardson]] and MVP [[Mateen Cleaves]] leading the team in a victory over the [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida Gators]].
Michigan State basketball has been selected for 14 consecutive NCAA tournament bids (1998&ndash;2011) as of the end of the 2010 season, which is the third-longest active streak of NCAA tournament bids, behind [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas]] (22) and [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (16). Overall, Michigan State has been to the Final Four a total of eight times in its history (1957, 1979, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2005, 2009, and 2010), which is tied for seventh all time, and has made 25 NCAA Tournament appearances. Only six schools have more total [[NCAA Men's Division I Final Four appearances by school|Final Four appearances]].<ref>[[NCAA Men's Division I Final Four appearances by school]]</ref> The program is also fourth all time in NCAA tournament winning percentage.
On December 13, 2003, Michigan State and [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]] played at the most-attended college basketball game in history known as the [[Basketbowl]]. They played this game in front of 78,129 people at [[Ford Field]], a football stadium converted to a basketball court for this game in [[Detroit]]. Kentucky won this game by a score of 79&ndash;74.<ref>MSU Spartans.com [http://msuspartans.collegesports.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/121303aaa.html Men's Basketball Falls To No. 8 Kentucky, 79-74].</ref>
==Coaches== Michigan State coaches have led the Spartans to two NCAA Championships, eight Final Fours, 25 NCAA Tournament appearances, 12 [[Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball regular season champions|Big Ten Conference Championships]] and two [[Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Big Ten Tournament]] titles. Michigan State has two coaches that are in the National Collegiate Basketball Hall of Fame (Pete Newell (class of 2006) and Jud Heathcote (class of 2009)). On November 28, 2009 Tom Izzo passed Jud Heathcote's mark of 340 career wins by beating U Mass 106-68. Tom Izzo now leads all MSU basketball coaches in wins.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://msuspartans.cstv.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/msu/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/mbaskbl-0708-mg-eight Michigan State Michigan State University Spartans, Official Athletic Site - Michigan State<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
